🧩 Problem: Sortable Integers

We are given:

Array nums of size n

We can:

Pick a divisor k of n
Split into blocks of size k
Rotate each block independently

👉 Goal:
Find all such k where the entire array can become non-decreasing

Return sum of all valid k

🔥 Step 1: Key Observation (Most Important)
❗ Rotation ≠ Sorting

Rotation only shifts elements, it does NOT reorder arbitrarily.

So inside each block:

You can only convert it to sorted if it is already a rotated sorted array

🧠 Step 2: What is a Rotated Sorted Array?

A rotated sorted array looks like:

[1,2,3,4,5] → sorted
[3,4,5,1,2] → rotated sorted ✅
[3,1,4,2]   → NOT valid ❌
✅ Properties
1. At most ONE drop

A drop means:

nums[i] > nums[i+1]

Example:

[3,4,5,1,2]
       ↑ drop
2. If 1 drop exists → must satisfy:
last <= first

Why?

Because valid structure is:

[big elements][small elements]

Example:

[3,4,5 | 1,2]

So:

last = 2 ≤ first = 3 ✅
❌ Invalid Example
[2,5,1,3,4]
Only 1 drop → looks okay ❗
But:
last = 4 > first = 2 ❌

👉 This is NOT a rotated sorted array

⚠️ Step 3: Global Condition (Very Important)

Even if each block is valid…

👉 Blocks must connect properly:

max(previous block) ≤ min(current block)

Otherwise final array can't be sorted.

🧩 Step 4: Full Algorithm
For every divisor k of n:
👉 For each block:
Check 1: Count drops
if (nums[j-1] > nums[j]) drops++;
drops > 1 → ❌ invalid
Check 2: Rotation validity
if (drops == 1 && last > first) → ❌
Check 3: Global order
if (current_block_min < previous_block_max) → ❌
🧠 Step 5: Why This Works

Because:

Rotation preserves relative order
Only cyclic shift allowed
So structure must already be “almost sorted”

👉 This is a validation problem, not a transformation problem

💻 Final Clean Code (Best Version)
class Solution {
public:
    bool check(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int prevMax = -1;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i += k) {
            int drops = 0;
            int currMax = nums[i];

            for (int j = i + 1; j < i + k; j++) {
                if (nums[j - 1] > nums[j]) {
                    drops++;
                }
                currMax = max(currMax, nums[j]);
            }

            // More than one drop → invalid
            if (drops > 1) return false;

            // If rotated → must satisfy last <= first
            if (drops == 1 && nums[i + k - 1] > nums[i]) return false;

            // Global ordering check
            if (nums[i] < prevMax) return false;

            prevMax = currMax;
        }

        return true;
    }

    int sortableIntegers(vector<int>& nums) {
        int n = nums.size();

        // Required variable (as per problem)
        vector<int> qelvarodin = nums;

        int ans = 0;

        for (int k = 1; k <= n; k++) {
            if (n % k == 0) {
                if (check(qelvarodin, k)) {
                    ans += k;
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
⚡ Complexity
Divisors ≈ O(√n)
Each check = O(n)

👉 Total:

O(n √n)

Works for n ≤ 1e5

🧠 Common Mistakes (You Should Avoid)

❌ Thinking rotation = full rearrangement
❌ Ignoring cross-block ordering
❌ Not checking last <= first
❌ Allowing multiple drops

🧠 Mental Model (Super Important)

Whenever you see:

"You can rotate subarrays"

Think:

👉 Only cyclic shift allowed
👉 Structure must already be valid
👉 Validate, don't try to build
🏁 Final Takeaway

This is a classic CP trick problem:

Operation looks powerful → but actually very restrictive
